msContents.summary: Collection of astronomical works, including 2 on the astrolabe (f. 1v-20v, 163r-168v), a treatise on a horoscope (f. 157v-160v) referring to Khawaja Haji Ghulām Ḥusayn and the date A.H. 1047 (1636, a date of birth?), and an illustrated work on Dhu al-Qarnayn, a Koranic figure later associated with legends of Alexander the Great (f. 137r-157r). Possibly copied by madrasah students, with some annotations.

msItem.title: Astrological compendium
msItem.author: Shīrāzī, Nāṣir ibn Ḥaydar ibn Muḥammad
Taqī Fārsī, Abū al-Khayr Muḥammad

msItem.title: On the eclipse of the moon from the sayings of the Prophet Daniel, f. 21r
Collection of treatises and tables, f. 22r
On astronomy and the astrolabe, f. 163r

supportDesc.extent: 168 leaves : 194 x 128 mm. bound to 196 x 135 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, i + 168 + i; [1-168], modern foliation in pencil, upper left recto.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in varying numbers of long lines.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in nastaʻlīq script by multiple hands.

decoDesc.decoNote: Ink drawings in the Dhakhīrat Iskandar Dhu al-Qarnayn of an animal, perhaps a jackal (f. 149v), 2 worms with pincers (f. 150v), hybrids of a snake with an animal's head and a person with a snake's tail (f. 151r), a scorpion (f. 151v), a crane (f. 152v), a youth with one hand on his head (f. 153r), and a rougher, sexual drawing of a man and a woman (f. 154v); tables in red and black (f. 41r-107r); significant words or phrases and headings in red throughout.
Drawing, Serpent with animal's head, f. 151r
Drawing, Man with serpent's tail, f. 151r
Drawing, Youth with one hand on his head, f. 153r
Drawing, Sexual drawing of man and woman, f. 154v

binding.p: Morocco with painted gilt borders, stamped with medallions and the name Ibrāhīm ibn Muḥammad Bāqir; morocco doublures.

origin.p: Written at the madrasah of ʻAlī Jāh Maḥmūd Beg Nāẓir, ca. 1670 (works dated on f. 136v, 157r, 168v), probably in Iṣfahān (f. 136v) in Persia, now Iran.

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan; sold at auction as part of his collection at Piasa (Paris), 7 June 1999.
Sold by Sam Fogg Ltd. (London) to Lawrence J. Schoenberg, Mar. 2001.
Deposit by Lawrence J. Schoenberg and Barbara Brizdle, 2011.
